sect3.para:
The Mini-International Neuropsychiatric Interview (MINI)
               Mini-International Neuropsychiatric Interview (MINI)
             is a brief structured diagnostic interview for major psychiatric disorders as defined in DSM-III-R, DSM-IV, DSM-5, as well as ICD-10 (Sheehan et al., 
               1998
            ). The MINI was designed to assess 17 of the most common psychiatric disorders, including PTSD, mania and hypomania, major depressive disorder, panic disorder, agoraphobia, social phobia, substance use disorder, and more. Specifically developed to be brief, administration of the MINI takes approximately 15 min, which is significantly shorter than the SCID (Sheehan et al., 
               1998
            ). In addition, the MINI was designed to be used by trained interviewers rather than physicians or mental health professionals (Sheehan et al., 
               1998
            ). There are more than 15 versions of the MINI, each addressing a different disorder and different population (e. g., adults, children, clinician-rated or patient-version). The most appropriate module for PTSD appears to be the Standard MINI, which assesses all 17 disorders.

Psychometrically, the MINI is a sound instrument and aligned with both the SCID-IV and ICD-10 for all 17 disorders. Specifically, the PTSD module shows significant sensitivity (>0.70) and very good positive predictive value (>0.75). Research also shows that the MINI has excellent inter-rater reliability (Interrater Kapa = 0.95) and good test-retest reliability (Test/Retest Kappa = 0.73) (Sheehan et al., 
               1998
            ). The measure has gained popularity among researchers worldwide and has been translated into multiple languages. This measure is useful for research purposes and as a supplemental measure of a more thorough interview, for diagnostic purposes.

Developed by the National Center for PTSD, the Life Events Checklist (LEC)
               Life Events Checklist (LEC)
             is a 17-item self-report measure that is aligned with DSM-5 criteria (Blake et al., 
               1995
            ). Unlike the majority of PTSD assessments that assess for most recent or current events, the LEC-5 assesses for potentially traumatic events across the lifespan. The person is asked if the event happened to them, was witnessed, was learned about from others, or if they are not sure or the event does not apply. The LEC-5 was initially intended to be used co-jointly with the CAPS. In a study by Gray et al. (
               2004
            ), the LEC was validated as an independent measurement for trauma events. Concerning the LEC’s reliability, the study found that all items except for one achieved a kappa above 0.50. At the same time, the test-retest correlation was exceptionally high (r = 0.82). As for validity, the study found strong convergence between the LEC and the Traumatic Life Events Questionnaire (TLEQ) scale, where only two of the nine items did not achieve a kappa of 0.40 (Gray et al., 
               2004
            ). It is important to note that while the LEC is primarily useful for identifying traumatic events as defined by PTSD or acute stress disorder, it can also be used to assess the severity of symptoms for an adjustment disorder.

The PTSD Checklist for Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (PCL) was initially developed by Weathers et al. (1993) and later redesigned by Weathers et al. (
               2013
            ) to align with DSM-5 criteria. It is a 20-item self-report measure used to screen for PTSD and to assess symptom severity. Respondents are asked to rate, on a scale from 0 (not at all) to 4 (extremely), how bothered they have been by each of the 20 items that correspond with DSM-5 criteria for PTSD. The two versions of the PCL-5, one for civilian and the other for military, are available in two formats, including a version with Criterion A (trauma) and one without. The PCL-5 was not developed as a standalone screening tool. It can supplement other, more structured, clinician-rated assessments and is quick and easy for clients to complete. It is also useful for monitoring symptoms over time, as the client can easily provide a self-report every few sessions.

Psychometric studies of the PCL prior to the DSM-5 version found the instrument to have high reliability and validity (Keen et al.,
               2008
            ). Blevins et al. (
               2015
            ) examined the psychometric properties of the current version and found excellent internal consistency (α = 0.94), strong test-retest reliability (r = 0.82), and good convergent and discriminant validities (rs = 0.74–0.85, and rs = 0.31–0.60, respectively). In another study, the PCL-5 similarly showed good internal consistency (α = 0.96) and test-retest reliability (r = 0.84) (Bovin et al., 
               2016
            ).

Developed by Prigerson et al. (
               1995
            ), the Inventory of Complicated Grief (ICG) is considered the most popular self-report tool to evaluate PGD. Its two main goals are to differentiate between prolonged grief and bereavement-related depression and anxiety and to predict long-term functional impairments (Prigerson et al., 
               1995
            ). The ICG includes 19 items that assess the frequency (i. e., from never to more than once daily) of experiences associated with grief, including “preoccupation with thoughts of the deceased, searching and yearning for the deceased, disbelief about the death, crying, being stunned by the death, and not accepting the death” (Prigerson et al.,
               1995
            ). In addition, high ICG scores (i. e., higher than 25) were indicative of a greater likelihood to have an impairment in various aspects of life, from physical health to social functioning (Prigerson et al.,
               1995
            ). The psychometric properties of the ICG are strong, with high internal consistency of the 19 items (Cronbach’s α = 0.94), test-retest reliability of 0.80, and concurrent validity with other tests of r = 0.67 and r = 0.87, P < 0.001.
